<HEAD>Volcano Erupts In Region of Japan Plagued By Earthquakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for 5th, ``Many people...'' to UPDATE with residents
calling local officials, second eruption not ruled out. Pickup 6th, ``More
than...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A volcano erupted near an uninhabited island today,
spewing plumes of steam and smoke into the air and raising concerns
about a region of the nation where thousands of earthquakes have
occurred recently.
   The eruption happened at <TIME>6:30 p.m.</TIME> about 1{ miles northeast of
the island of <LOCATION>Teishijima</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Central Meteorological Agency</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   The island is just off the coast of Ito city on the <LOCATION>Izu
peninsula</LOCATION>, 60 miles southwest of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>. The extent of the volcanic
activity several hundred yards beneath the ocean's surface was not
immediately known, the agency said.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries, and a tsunami, or
seismic wave caused by earthquakes or volcanic activity, was not
expected, the agency said. However, it issued a navigation warning
to ships operating in the area.
   Many people in <LOCATION>Ito</LOCATION>, a seaside spa known for its many hot springs,
were seen leaving their homes, but no evacuation order was issued,
the <ORGANIZATION>Japan Broadcasting Corp.</ORGANIZATION> said. Hundreds of people called local
officials asking about the volcano.
   ``Right now, we don't know if this will lead to another, larger
eruption and can only tell people there to watch for further
warnings,'' said a <ORGANIZATION>Central Meteorological Agency</ORGANIZATION> official who
requested anonymity. ``Obviously, there could be danger to <PERSON>Ito</PERSON> if a
larger eruption occurs.''
   More than 20,000 earthquakes have been recorded around <LOCATION>Izu</LOCATION> over
the past two weeks, and officials from the <ORGANIZATION>Construction Ministry</ORGANIZATION>'s
<ORGANIZATION>Geographical Survey Institute</ORGANIZATION> began today to check movement of the
earth's crust at <LOCATION>Ito</LOCATION>, the town nearest the epicenter. Ito has a
population of 72,000.
   Also seismologists from the <ORGANIZATION>University</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> started surveying
the movements of underground magma with monitoring equipment in <LOCATION>Ito</LOCATION>.
   The stepped-up investigations followed an emergency meeting late
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> of the government's <ORGANIZATION>Coordinating Committee for Earthquake
Prediction</ORGANIZATION>, which called for ``careful monitoring'' of the
continuing earthquakes.
   The 16-member committee, led by Professor <PERSON>Daisuke Shimozuru</PERSON> of
the <ORGANIZATION>University of Tokyo</ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement that the successive
minor quakes occurring since <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> ``may be caused by
activities of underground magma, and there is a need to monitor them
carefully.''
   Two million people visited <DATE>Ito last year</DATE>, where there are 450
inns and hotels for visitors, <PERSON>Hidekatsu Takei</PERSON>, acting director of
the <ORGANIZATION>Hot Spring Tourist Cooperatives</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Ito</LOCATION>, told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated
Press</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
