<HEAD>Quakes, Volcano Eruption Scare Tourists Away From Resort Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Yusaku Inoue</PERSON>, sitting quietly <DATE>Friday</DATE> on the
stairs in front of his tiny beachfront restaurant, sighed deeply and
said, ``It looks like my <DATE>summer</DATE> is over.''
   The 85-year-old restaurant owner was among hundreds of shop
owners, hotel managers and restaurant operators in <LOCATION>Ito</LOCATION>, 60 miles
southwest of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, whose business has been hurt by thousands of
earthquakes and the eruption of an undersea volcano.
   ``I have been running this place for over 40 years and business
was never this bad,'' he said.
   Since <DATE>June 30</DATE>, more than 22,000 quakes have jolted the hot
springs resort, including more than 585 strong enough to be felt by
humans. Twenty-one people suffered minor injuries when two
earthquakes registering 5.5 on the Richter scale hit Ito on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   On <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>, a volcano onthe ocean floor off Ito erupted,
spewing white steam into the air.
   The hundreds of hotels in the area are virtually empty, although
some of the rooms are being filled by reporters.
   ``The irony is that this town earned its fame from its rich hot
springs derived from volcanic activity,'' said one middle-aged shop
owner, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Now, the volcanic
activity is hurting the tourism industry.''
   More earthquakes and volcanic tremors jolted the Ito area on
<DATE>Friday</DATE>, but no injuries were reported. Scores of dead fish and
volcanic stones were scattered along the shore.
   ``On an ordinary <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, this beach is always packed
and most restaurants around here are full,'' said <PERSON>Inoue</PERSON>. ``But I've
only had one customer so far today.''
   News reports <DATE>Friday</DATE> said two undersea mounds were found near the
eruption site, a few miles from <PERSON>Ito</PERSON>. One was about 80 feet high and
the other about 30 feet, the reports said.
   Most of the 200 people who left their seaside houses after the
eruption to spend the night in four Buddhist temples and schools
returned home <DATE>Friday</DATE>, but 43 schools in <LOCATION>Ito</LOCATION> remained closed, said
<PERSON>Masaaki Mitsuhashi</PERSON>, a spokesman for the city.
   The government's <ORGANIZATION>Coordinating Committee for Earthquake Prediction</ORGANIZATION>
said another eruption was highly likely to occur, not only at the
same spot but possibly at other locations.
   When the 72,000 residents began to experience temblors in recent
weeks, its 916 hotels and inns began receiving a stream of
cancellations. After the eruption <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, more than <PERCENT>95 percent</PERCENT> of
hotel reservations were canceled, said <PERSON>Hiroyuki Yamashita</PERSON> of <PERSON>Ito</PERSON>'s
tourist bureau.
   The Japanese archipelago, which is of volcanic origin, is
believed to have about 80 active volcanoes. In <DATE>January</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Mount
Tokachi</ORGANIZATION>, on <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s northern island of <LOCATION>Hokkaido</LOCATION>, erupted several
times.
</TEXT>
