<HEAD>Rumbling Beneath Volcano Draws Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of small quakes have rattled an
Aleut fishing village during the past 17 days, and geologists say
they are keeping a wary eye on the possible source: a volcano
that's been dormant for centuries.
   King Cove village is only nine miles from <ORGANIZATION>Mount Dutton</ORGANIZATION>'s
4,834-foot peak. About 1,000 people live in the village during the
<DATE>summer</DATE>; 700 stay through winter.
   Aside from the earthquakes that have been jolting the community
625 miles southwest of <LOCATION>Anchorage</LOCATION>, there have been no other signs of
an imminent eruption, said <PERSON>Betsy Yount</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Geological Survey</ORGANIZATION>
geologist here.
   ``There's no melting back of snow around the summit. No
steam-type vents,'' sher said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. ``We're still assessing
the seismic activity to determine whether it's related to volcanic
activity or not.''
   Geologists are unsure when <ORGANIZATION>Mount Dutton</ORGANIZATION> last erupted.
   ``There's no historical records of its erupting. That means in
the past 200 or so years,'' said <PERSON>John Davies</PERSON>, state seismologist
and coordinating scientist for the newly formed <ORGANIZATION>Alaska Volcano
Observatory</ORGANIZATION>. ``It may have erupted 500 years ago, but we have no
date. Clearly, it's erupted in the last 10,000 years or so.''
   <PERSON>John Taber</PERSON>, a geologist with <ORGANIZATION>Columbia University</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Lamont
Doherty Geological Observatory</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Palisades</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, said
seismographs first picked up earthquake activity near <LOCATION>Mount Dutton</LOCATION>
on <DATE>July 11</DATE>. Some of the 18 instruments installed by the institute
to monitor Aleutian Arc volcanic activity indicated the first
temblors were centered 10 to 15 miles southeast of the peak, he
said.
   ``In the last three or four days its been dying off,'' <PERSON>Taber</PERSON>
said from the institute's Sand Point office. ``There's no cause for
concern at this point at all. There was a sequence of (earthquakes)
in <DATE>1984</DATE>. They were smaller, but they went on for about four months.
It's not even unusual to have them there.''
   Scores of quakes ranging from 1.0 to 3.6 on the Richter scale
have struck in this round. The peak activity occurred <DATE>Friday</DATE>, when
127 were recorded, <PERSON>Taber</PERSON> said. On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, there were 25, he said.
   The epicenters moved slowly toward the <PERSON>Mount Dutton</PERSON>, and in the
last few days, the centers have been underneath the volcano's south
flank, <PERSON>Taber</PERSON> said.
   The temblors have jolted the nearby village regularly. ``We've
felt four or five in a day, that's probably the most. But there's
no other sign of activity at all,'' said <PERSON>Cynthia Samuelson</PERSON>, city
clerk the village on the <LOCATION>Alaska Peninsula</LOCATION>. ``People are concerned,
but no one's leaving.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Alaska Division of Emergency Services</ORGANIZATION> officials had been
scheduled to travel to <ORGANIZATION>King Cove</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>September</DATE>, but went this week
because of the earthquakes, said <PERSON>Jim Sey</PERSON>, the agency's chief of
operations and planning.
   ``The main purpose was just to answer questions, make people
aware and bring them up to date on what's happening and explain
different things they could do if there were an eruption,'' <PERSON>Sey</PERSON>
said.
   A telephone line is being installed so that the <ORGANIZATION>Geophysical
Institute</ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION>University of Alaska-Fairbanks</ORGANIZATION> can monitor <PERSON>Taber</PERSON>'s
seismographs, plus one <PERSON>Davies</PERSON> recently installed on the mountain's
flank. Taber has been in <LOCATION>Alaska</LOCATION> servicing his observatory's
seismographs and plans to leave this week, <PERSON>Davies</PERSON> said.
   The link will allow scientists in <LOCATION>Fairbanks</LOCATION> to check the
volcano's pulse virtually around the clock, he said.
   ``We're going to monitor it as closely as we can,'' he said.
</TEXT>
