<HEAD>Light Tremors Shake Mount Etna, Volcano Spits Ash, Rocks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CATANIA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hot ash and rocks shot from <LOCATION>Mount Etna</LOCATION>
and fell on nearby hamlets during a snowstorm, experts said.
   Seismologists at the <ORGANIZATION>International Volcanology Institute</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Catania</LOCATION>, the Sicilian city lying at the foot of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>'s most
active volcano, also said a series of tremors rattled the top of
<LOCATION>Mount Etna</LOCATION> over several hours early <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   The southeastern crater of the volcano spit hot ash and lava
rock, which fell on the villages of <LOCATION>Maletto</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Bronte</PERSON> and <PERSON>Randazzo</PERSON>
during a snowstorm, the seismologists said. No one was injured and
no damage was reported.
   Bad weather conditions did not allow volcanologists to observe
the eruption at close range, but they said it did not appear lava
had flowed down the side of the volcano.
</TEXT>
