<HEAD>Volcanic Activity On The Rise In Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A volcano erupted near here, and another
crater spewed ash and steam in <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>, but officials in the two
Central American countries said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> they had no immediate
reports of major damage or injuries.
   <PERSON>Eddy Sanchez</PERSON>, deputy director of <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Seismological
Institute</ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview that 255 residents of two villages
on the slopes of the <LOCATION>Pacaya Volcano</LOCATION> were forced to evacuate their
homes because of lava flows.
   Pacaya, 16 miles south of the capital, started spewing lava
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>. About 175 people in the village of <ORGANIZATION>El Caracol</ORGANIZATION> and
80 from <LOCATION>El Patrocinio</LOCATION> cleared out of their homes <DATE>late Wednesday</DATE>,
hours ahead of a small river of lava that destroyed their
coffee-bean fields.
   But a number of farmers in other villages in the area stayed
behind, <PERSON>Sanchez</PERSON> said. He said the lava is flowing down <LOCATION>Pacaya</LOCATION>'s
slopes in a southeasterly direction at about 15 feet an hour.
   The 8,421-foot peak, one of 32 volcanos dotting <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>, has
been erupting intermittently since it first turned active <DATE>Jan 21,
1987</DATE>. On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the volcano blew open a new crater.
   ``The Pacaya continues active, spewing out lava with constant
explosions,'' <PERSON>Sanchez</PERSON> said.
   In <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> volcano, 12 miles southeast of the
capital, <LOCATION>Managua</LOCATION>, began releasing white gases on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, but
scientists monitoring the activity say there is no immediate danger
of an eruption.
   <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> is one of three in the <LOCATION>Masaya</LOCATION> complex, one of the most
active volcanic ranges in <LOCATION>Central America</LOCATION>. Its single crater has
been releasing gases about once every two decades.
   Lava flows often have followed the initial eruptions, but they
solidified before reaching populated areas.
   <PERSON>Favio Segura</PERSON>, an engineer with the <ORGANIZATION>Nicaraguan Institute of
Territorial Studies</ORGANIZATION>, told reporters, ``It is difficult to predict if
<LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> will develop a large or small lava flow.''
   He said three Nicaraguan and three British vulcanologists are
monitoring the peak around the clock.
   The <ORGANIZATION>National Association of Geologists</ORGANIZATION> has reported no
``immediate risk of a violent explosion that would endanger
surrounding communities.''
</TEXT>
