<HEAD>Say Dives Exciting, But No Hot Springs Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRATER LAKE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists' first dives to the bottom
of Crater Lake turned up no signs of expected hot springs that
might be evidence of ancient volcanic activity, but their submarine
ride gave them a new outlook.
   ``I think so far we have seen similar things, but in much
greater detail than last year,'' when a robot submarine explored
the lake, <ORGANIZATION>Oregon State University</ORGANIZATION> oceanographer <PERSON>Jack Dymond</PERSON> said
<DATE>Sunday</DATE>, describing the first two dives.
   ``We haven't found any actual thermal springs,'' said <PERSON>Dymond</PERSON>,
who made the first manned dive to the bottom of the nation's
deepest lake <DATE>Friday</DATE>. The deepest point in the lake is 1,932 feet.
   Dymond and fellow <ORGANIZATION>OSU</ORGANIZATION> oceanographer <PERSON>Robert Collier</PERSON> are using a
one-man submersible called Deep Rover to search the lake for hot
springs that may be the remnants of volcanic activity that formed
the lake.
   <PERSON>Dymond</PERSON> said he saw what he interpreted as evidence of old hot
springs: deposits of iron and manganese and rock formations with
colored stains on holes or cracks.
   The research could affect efforts by <ORGANIZATION>California Energy Co.</ORGANIZATION> to
develop hydrothermal energy nearby, outside the boundary of <ORGANIZATION>Crater
Lake National Park</ORGANIZATION>. If the lake is found to have significant
geothermal features, development in the neighboring <ORGANIZATION>Winema National
Forest</ORGANIZATION> could be prohibited.
   The two men are in the second year of a three-year effort
financed by the <ORGANIZATION>National Park Service</ORGANIZATION> to learn why the lake's water
is so clear, with visibility measured to depths of 85 to 115 feet.
   <PERSON>Collier</PERSON>, who made his first dive <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, said that at a depth
of 1,200 feet blue light was still visible from above.
   Their work is part of a larger 10-year study started after
scientists in the <DATE>1970s</DATE> noticed a significant reduction in the
lake's clarity. Recent measurements have shown the clarity
returning to levels last measured in the <DATE>1930s</DATE>.
   Dymond and <PERSON>Collier</PERSON> said nothing they have found so far could
settle the question of whether drilling for hydrothermal energy
more than seven miles away would affect the lake.
   <ORGANIZATION>California Energy Co.</ORGANIZATION> geologist <PERSON>Joe LaFleur</PERSON> said if hot springs
do exist, they wouldn't be affected by the drilling.
   Crater Lake was formed after rain and melted snow filled a
crater, called a caldera, formed when the <LOCATION>Mount Mazama</LOCATION> volcano
erupted nearly 7,000 years ago and then collapsed into what had
been a chamber filled with molten rock.
   Collier and <PERSON>Dymond</PERSON> said sonar echos off unexpectedly craggy
features on the bottom of the lake made precise navigation
difficult.
   Precise navigation is important. Last year, while using the
remote-controlled submersible, scientists found what looked like a
vent oozing a milky fluid. However, they were never able to
relocate it to take a temperature reading or a fluid sample.
</TEXT>
