<HEAD>Northern Japanese Town Alert to Possible Volcanic Eruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People living near a volcano in northern <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> that
came to life last month for the first time in 26 years are bracing
themselves for another powerful eruption.
   Scientists studying the volcano said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> there were signs
another major eruption was developing.
   ``Based on the volume of magma that exists there may be a major,
powerful eruption to match'' those that occurred in <DATE>1926</DATE> and <DATE>1962</DATE>,
said <PERSON>Yoshio Fujii</PERSON>, professor on volcanology and petrology at
<ORGANIZATION>Hokkaido University</ORGANIZATION>.
   Fujii based his prediction on analysis of rock samples taken from
nearby peaks following the <DATE>Dec. 19</DATE> eruption of the 6,814-foot <LOCATION>Mount
Tokachi</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>central Hokkaido</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s northernmost main island.
   <PERSON>Koichi Ueda</PERSON>, an official of Kamifurano-cho, a town of 14,000
people just 15 miles from <LOCATION>Mount Tokachi</LOCATION>, said 13 town officials were
maintaining an around-the-clock watch.
   No damage or injuries were reported in the <DATE>Dec. 19</DATE> eruption.
   Heat from <LOCATION>Mount Tokachi</LOCATION>'s eruption in <DATE>1926</DATE> melted almost all the
snow on the mountain, causing mudslides that killed 144 people and
injured another 200 in two nearby villages. A smaller eruption in
<DATE>1962</DATE> killed four people.
   Activity inside <LOCATION>Mount Tokachi</LOCATION> has intensified since <DATE>Jan. 9</DATE>
because magma is rising from deep within the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> to about 1,650
feet below the crater of the volcano, according to <PERSON>Hiroshi Okada</PERSON>,
head of <ORGANIZATION>Hokkaido University</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Usu volcano Observatory</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``The form of volcanic activity has started changing,''
indicating the possibility of an explosion of magma from the
mountain, <ORGANIZATION>Kyodo News Service</ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON>Okada</PERSON> as saying.
</TEXT>
