<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Hits Volcanic Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake rocked the volcanic island of
<LOCATION>Oshima</LOCATION> near <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> early <DATE>Saturday</DATE> and caused buildings to sway in
<LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, but no immediate sign of eruptions or reports of damage or
casualties followed.
   The quake struck at <TIME>6:20 a.m</TIME>. It had a preliminary reading of
5.9 on the Richter scale on <LOCATION>Oshima</LOCATION>, nearly 75 miles south of the
Japanese capital, and in <LOCATION>Yokohama</LOCATION>, just south of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, according
to the <ORGANIZATION>Central Meteorological Agency
   Meteorologists</ORGANIZATION> said the quake was centered 25 miles below the
ocean surface near <LOCATION>Oshima</LOCATION>.
   A <ORGANIZATION>Metropolitan Police Department</ORGANIZATION> official said police received
no reports of damage or injury.
   <PERSON>Mt. Mihara</PERSON>, an active volcano on <LOCATION>Oshima</LOCATION>, erupted in <DATE>November
1986</DATE>, spewing molten rock high into the air and forcing more than
11,000 people to evacuate. No direct casualties resulted, though
one person died later of a heart attack.
   A milder eruption occurred a year later. Oshima is part of an
island chain considered to be one of the most volcanically active
in the world.
   The open-ended Richter scale ia a gauge of energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage
and one of magnitude 6, severe damage.
</TEXT>
